{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Picks up his top.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Everything's fine.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BACK ROOM, WORKSHOP - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Close on a small BRASS CHESS PIECE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne tips it over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frowning, she picks up a micro drill, peels back the felt on the bottom and widens a hole in one side of its base.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tests the TIPPING POINT again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A NOISE makes her look up.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WORKSHOP - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne comes into the main space.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Someone is there, unpacking one of the MECHANISMS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: You're back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb looks up with a start.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Caught out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Are you going under on your own?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: I just-I need to test some things.
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't realize anyone was here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Just working on my totem.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne holds up the chess piece.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb reaches for it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Let me see-
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne SNAPS it out of his reach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Smiles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: You're learning.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: It's an elegant solution to keeping track of reality.
{DIALOGUE}: Your invention?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: Mal's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb pulls out his spinning top.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looks at it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 55.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: This one was hers.
{DIALOGUE}: She'd spin it in a dream and it would never topple.
{DIALOGUE}: Just spin and spin...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Arthur told me she died.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: She did.
{DIALOGUE}: How are the mazes coming?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne indicates three large ARCHITECTURAL MODELS.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Good.
{DIALOGUE}: Each level relates to the part of the subject's subconscious we're trying to access.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm making the bottom level a hospital, so that Fischer will bring his father there-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Don't tell me.
{DIALOGUE}: Remember, you only want the dreamer to know the layout.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Why's that so important?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: In case one of us brings in part of our subconscious.
{DIALOGUE}: You wouldn't want any projections knowing the layout.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: In case you bring Mal in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb says nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: You won't build yourself because if you know the maze, then she knows it.
{DIALOGUE}: And she'd sabotage the operation.
{DIALOGUE}: You can't keep her out, can you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb says nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Do the others know?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: No. 56.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: You have to warn them if it's getting worse-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{META_DATA}: (gentle)
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't say it's getting worse.
{DIALOGUE}: Look, Ariadne, I need them for this job.
{DIALOGUE}: I need you for this job.
{DIALOGUE}: Without your help, I'll never get back to my children.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's all I can care about right now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: Why can't you go home, Cobb?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb looks at her, deciding what to say.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: They think I killed her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: How did she die?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb thinks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSERT CUT: Mal, wind BLOWING her hair, smiles at Cobb.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now we see Cobb- SHAKING HIS HEAD, TEARS STREAMING, BEGGING-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARIADNE
{DIALOGUE}: For what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Not asking whether I did.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. WORKSHOP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne, Arthur, Yusuf, Eames and Saito sit around the room, looking at FILES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb presides.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: The mark is Robert Fischer, heir to the Australian energy conglomerate, Fischer Morrow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb opens a large presentation pad.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COBB (reads aloud) "I WILL SPLIT UP MY FATHER'S EMPIRE."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb turns to the team.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 57.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: An idea Robert Fischer's conscious mind would never accept.
{DIALOGUE}: We have to plant it deep in his subconscious.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: How deep?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Three levels down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: A dream within a dream within a dream?
{DIALOGUE}: Is that even possible?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: It is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Now, the subconscious motivates through emotion, not reason, so we have to translate the idea into an emotional concept.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: How do you translate a business strategy into an emotion?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: That's what we have to figure out.
{DIALOGUE}: Robert and his father have a tense relationship.
{DIALOGUE}: Worse, even, than the gossip columns have suggested...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: Do you play on that?
{DIALOGUE}: Suggest breaking up his father's company as a 'screw you' to the old man?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: Positive emotion trumps negative emotion every time.
{DIALOGUE}: We yearn for people to be reconciled, for catharsis.
{DIALOGUE}: We need positive emotional logic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eames thinks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Paces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking back at the board.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: Try this... "MY FATHER ACCEPTS THAT I WANT TO CREATE FOR MYSELF, NOT FOLLOW IN HIS FOOTSTEPS."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: That might work.
{DIALOGUE}: 58.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: Might?
{DIALOGUE}: We'll have to do better than that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks for the contribution, Arthur.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: Forgive me for wanting a little specificity, Eames.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Inception's not about specificity.
{DIALOGUE}: When we get inside his head, we're going to have to work with what we find.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Arthur shrugs, frustrated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And we-
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NEW YORK STREETS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The team are in the middle of a DESERTED intersection.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ariadne is showing Yusuf aspects of the geography.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: We could split the idea into emotional triggers, and use one on each level.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: How do you mean?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: On the top level, we open up his relationship with his father....
{DIALOGUE}: Say: "I WILL NOT FOLLOW IN MY FATHER'S FOOTSTEPS."
{DIALOGUE}: Next level down we've accessed his ambition and self-esteem.
{DIALOGUE}: We feed him: "I WILL CREATE SOMETHING MYSELF."
{DIALOGUE}: Then, the bottom level, we bring out the emotional big guns...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: "MY FATHER DOESN'T WANT ME TO BE HIM."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: That could do it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: How do you produce these emotional triggers?
{DIALOGUE}: 59.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EAMES
{DIALOGUE}: I forge each emotional concept in the style and manner of Peter Browning, a key figure in Fischer's emotional life.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two AFRICAN PEDESTRIANS wander into view.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: Are those yours?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eames shakes his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cobb turns to Yusuf.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARTHUR
{DIALOGUE}: Yusuf?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: YUSUF
{DIALOGUE}: Yup.
{DIALOGUE}: Sorry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COBB
{DIALOGUE}: Suppress them.
{DIALOGUE}: We don't bring our own projections into the dream-we let Fischer's subconscious supply the people.
